
<recipe>
  <title>Spaghetti Carbonara</title>
  <author>
    <name>John Doe</name>
    <profileUrl>https://example.com/johndoe</profileUrl>
  </author>
  <ingredients>
    <ingredient>
      <name>Spaghetti</name>
      <quantity>400</quantity>
      <unit>grams</unit>
    </ingredient>
    <ingredient>
      <name>Guanciale</name>
      <quantity>150</quantity>
      <unit>grams</unit>
    </ingredient>
    <ingredient>
      <name>Eggs</name>
      <quantity>4</quantity>
      <unit>pieces</unit>
    </ingredient>
    <ingredient>
      <name>Parmesan Cheese</name>
      <quantity>50</quantity>
      <unit>grams</unit>
    </ingredient>
    <ingredient>
      <name>Black Pepper</name>
      <quantity>1</quantity>
      <unit>teaspoon</unit>
    </ingredient>
  </ingredients>
  <steps>
    <step>
      <order>1</order>
      <instruction>Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add spaghetti and cook until al dente.</instruction>
      <durationMinutes>10</durationMinutes>
    </step>
    <step>
      <order>2</order>
      <instruction>In a separate pan, cook guanciale over medium heat until crispy. Remove from pan and set aside.</instruction>
      <durationMinutes>5</durationMinutes>
    </step>
    <step>
      <order>3</order>
      <instruction>Drain spaghetti and reserve 1/2 cup of pasta water. Add spaghetti to the pan with guanciale and toss to combine.</instruction>
      <durationMinutes>2</durationMinutes>
    </step>
    <step>
      <order>4</order>
      <instruction>In a bowl, whisk together eggs, Parmesan cheese, and black pepper. Gradually pour the egg mixture over the spaghetti, tossing to coat.</instruction>
      <durationMinutes>2</durationMinutes>
    </step>
    <step>
      <order>5</order>
      <instruction>If the sauce is too thick, add some reserved pasta water. Serve immediately.</instruction>
      <durationMinutes>1</durationMinutes>
    </step>
  </steps>
